1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)
🔹 Why the Constitution is Important

The Constitution of India is the supreme law of the country.
It defines:

Structure of government

Powers of institutions

Rights of citizens

📌 Adopted on 26 November 1949
📌 Came into force on 26 January 1950

🔵 Historical Background

The Constitution evolved through several British laws.

1️⃣ Regulating Act (1773)

First step of British parliamentary control

Governor of Bengal became Governor-General

Supreme Court established in Calcutta

2️⃣ Pitt’s India Act (1784)

Introduced dual control

Board of Control + East India Company

3️⃣ Charter Act (1833)

Governor-General of Bengal became Governor-General of India

Lord William Bentinck first GG of India

4️⃣ Government of India Act (1858)

End of East India Company rule

Power transferred to British Crown

5️⃣ Indian Councils Act (1909) – Morley–Minto Reforms

Introduced separate electorates

6️⃣ Government of India Act (1919)

Introduced Dyarchy in provinces

7️⃣ Government of India Act (1935)

📌 Most important act

Features:

Federal structure

Provincial autonomy

Federal Court

Many provisions of today’s Constitution came from this Act.

🔹 Sources of Indian Constitution
Source	Borrowed Feature
UK	Parliamentary system
USA	Fundamental Rights
Ireland	Directive Principles
Canada	Federal system with strong centre
Australia	Concurrent List
Germany	Emergency provisions
🔹 Key Features of Indian Constitution

Longest written constitution

Federal with unitary features

Parliamentary democracy

Independent judiciary

Fundamental rights

